snippet.textDisplay: I'm not ashamed to say that I've cried several times this week since hearing the news about Kobe, his daughter, and seven other people being killed in that tragic crash. For the past couple of days I've held it together, but....watching those clips of Kobe set to that version of "Hero" set me off again. And I truly thank you for that (not that I like crying, but...it was very cathartic so thank you for that choice). Also, thanks Jimmy for taking a night to remember some great interviews with a man who, while not perfect, was (and still remains) a huge part of the soul of Los Angeles. I don't live there anymore, but...that man was special. I had one not-good interaction with Kobe in the 1990s, not long after he was drafted, and I thought he was a jerk -- but then I watched him grow up to be the man he was. He had his foibles along the way, but he grew up to be someone I respected a LOT. He worked his tail off to EARN that respect -- not just on the court, but as a father.

snippet.textDisplay: The Chicago Bulls have been my favorite team my entire life, I'm not a Lakers fan by any means......but I first watched this guy in The McDonalds All American game, and me being a Michael Jordan fan hearing about Harold Miner, Grant Hill, and countless others being the "next" Jordan which I would always laugh off.....With Kobe.......I cannot, will not, lie....I SEEN IT, COULDN'T DENY THIS ONE.....HE WAS THAT GUY, EVEN THOUGH HE DIDN'T PLAY FOR MY BULLS.....I LOVE THIS GUY LIKE I LOVE JORDAN....THIS IS INCREDIBLY PAINFUL TO DEAL WITH.  THINKING ABOUT EVERYONE ON THE HELICOPTER WHO I DON'T KNOW ALSO....R.I.P...CONDOLENCES TO THEIR FRIEND AND FAMILY.  EVERYONE WHO HAS STUPID PROBLEMS WITH PEOPLE, LET THAT GO....ITS NOT WORTH USING THAT ENERGY FOR THAT WHEN IT CAN GO IN A POSITIVE DIRECTION.  REACH OUT AND LET YOUR PEOPLE KNOW YOU LOVE THEM.....WE ALL HAVE A DATE IN THAT BOOK WHEN WE WILL LEAVE THE EARTH, WE JUST DON'T, AND NEVER WILL KNOW WHEN THAT DAY IS, SO LIVE EVERYDAY LIKE ITS YOUR LAST ONE.  R.I.P. YOUNG KOBE, WE LOVE YOU AND WILL NEVER FORGET YOU....GLAD I GOT TO SEE YOU PLAY IN PERSON...R.I.P. GIGI.  BLESS YOUR SOULS.

snippet.textDisplay: This is by far my favorite tribute video for him. It shows his true character and not just a really good basketball player. He's a human being with all human being qualities. He had enemies, he made mistakes, some big mistakes, he has so many true friends, a beautiful family. He wasn't a hero or legend in the sense that he changed the world or saved lives, but in everyone's own personal way that loved and or looked up to him. A boy or girl that could've gotten sucked into these streets heard about him and his story and choose to pursue their dreams due to him. Who knows how many lives he had an influence on without even knowing it. And that was his purpose. He would be doing the same thing for the same reasons without all the success because that's just who he was. He loved life just as much as life loved him. And his poor baby girl that lost her life...and how his family is going to deal without the two of them- is so heartbreaking. He wasn't the worlds hero, he was everyone who loved him hero. RIP K and Gigi.

snippet.textDisplay: In July 2003, Bryant was charged with sexually assaulting a 19-year-old employee of the Lodge and Spa at Cordillera in Edwards, Colo. He admitted that he didn’t explicitly ask for consent and initially denied even having sex with the woman. He left a bruise on her neck and drew blood from her skin. After Bryant’s defense team badly intimidated the victim and smeared her reputation, she refused to testify.
